				<li id="16796007" class="cmnt-root" data="0" data-d="1668134458000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><a class="comment-username" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&u=163490" rel="nofollow"  target="_blank" style="color: #;">JacobEsterson</a></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t578301/Black-Bow" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">10 Nov 2022 21:40</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16796007" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">I can&apos;t talk enough about how people are sleeping on bow builds, and after my first Elden Ring bow run I am now entirely convinced that in terms of early game potential, they reign supreme. I wouldn&apos;t recommend it for a new player on a first run, because you need to upgrade your bow FAST and that obviously requires a higher level of general game knowledge to do efficiently.<br/><br/>The route seems to be: wrong warping into Lyndell for the Black Bow, which is still easily doable on current patch - scavenging around the map for as many low level sombre smithing stones as possible - grabbing the two most important talismans (Arrow&apos;s Sting talisman from Caelid, Blue Dancer Charm from Limgrave) - and finishing Varré&apos;s questline for an ancient dragon sombre stone and access to bird farming.<br/><br/>(Most somber stones 1 through 9 are easy to get just via running around, the hardest one is likely to be somber stone 7 which is blocked by Godskin Noble in Volcano Manor. I don&apos;t know if Noble is still skippable but it&apos;s easy enough to beat it with a +6 bow anyway)<br/><br/>The above steps are all easily accomplishable within a few hours, and by the time you&apos;re done you&apos;ll feel like a god. I no-hit literally every single shardbearer effortlessly without even trying. They all die so fast it&apos;s unreal. I&apos;ve never done any of them no-hit, and I wasn&apos;t intending to. It literally just... Happened...<br/><br/>Now I don&apos;t want to overstate things. I haven&apos;t gotten to mountaintops quite yet, so maybe the damage will fall off to the point where it doesn&apos;t feel so strong anymore. But over 400 AR (this is with Ritual Sword and 30/59 STR/DEX) on such a safe weapon is nuts no matter how you look at it. Add status effect arrows and it gets even dumber.<br/><br/>Unlike with mages you don&apos;t have to worry about splitting flasks for FP so you can literally just go full 15 health flasks, but with ALL the safety of a rangey mage. In fact, you actually have far MORE range than a mage. I&apos;m actually understating how dumb this is, because not only do you not have to bring any FP flasks, but you NEVER run out of FP like a mage build because of the hundreds of arrows you can carry. Buying arrows is a complete non issue because of how easy it is to just casually bird-farm 100k runes and buy max storage capacity of your given arrow type. All you do is kite, and win. It&apos;s that simple.</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16796007" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16796007" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">0</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>0</p><i class="add">+1</i></section><section class="t-down"><span></span><p>0</p><i class="sub">-1</i></section>